# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cryengine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cryengine/cryengine] According to various anonymous reports in April 2015, CryEngine was licensed to Amazon for $50–70 million.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] Consequently, in February 2016, Amazon released its own reworked and extended version of CryEngine under the name of Amazon Lumberyard.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] In June 2021, through Amazon Lumberyard, the open-source Open 3D Engine is based on CryEngine.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] CryEngine 1 was first made and used for the first-person shooter video game *Far Cry*.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] It was originally developed by Crytek as a technology demo for Nvidia and, when the company saw its potential, it was turned into a game.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] When video cards with support for 3.0 pixel and vertex shaders were released, Crytek released version 1.2 of the engine which used some of the capabilities for better graphics.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] Later the company developed CryEngine version 1.3, which added support for HDR lighting.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] The engine has been licensed to NCsoft for their MMORPG, *Aion: The Tower of Eternity*.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] On March 30, 2006, Ubisoft acquired all intellectual property rights to the *Far Cry* franchise and a perpetual license to use the *Far Cry* edition of CryEngine, known as the Dunia Engine.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] CryEngine 2 is used in Crytek's game *Crysis*, and an updated version in *Crysis Warhead*, a side story of *Crysis*.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] It was first licensed out to French company IMAGTP who specializes in architectural and urban-planning communication.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] The purpose of licensing the engine was to create a program to allow clients to see exactly what a building or other structure would look like before any actual construction was started.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] As of March 7, 2011, Simpson Studios has licensed CryEngine 2 out to use on a Massively Multiplayer Virtual World (MMVW) that takes place on a terraformed Mars.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] On May 11, 2007, Crytek announced that they would be using the engine to create a game based on their new intellectual property.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] It is also confirmed that it would not be a part of *Crysis* and in fact may not even be a first-person shooter.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] On September 17, 2007, Ringling College of Art & Design became the first higher education institution in the world to license CryEngine 2 for educational purposes.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] Crytek introduced CryEngine 3 at the 2009 Game Developers Conference, held from March 25 to March 27 and demonstrated it on the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 consoles.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] The new engine was being developed for use on Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, and Wii U.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] As for the PC platform, the engine is said to support development in DirectX 9, 10, and 11.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] As of June 1, 2009, it was announced that *Crysis 2* would be developed by Crytek on their brand-new engine.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] CryEngine 3 was released on October 14, 2009.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] On March 1, 2010, a new tech demo of the engine was released for the i3D 2010 symposium, which demonstrates 'Cascaded Light Propagation Volumes for Real Time Indirect Illumination'.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] On June 11, 2011, the Australian Defence Force revealed that Navy personnel would train on a virtual landing helicopter dock ship made using the CryEngine 3 software.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] As of July 1, 2011, the Mod SDK version of CryEngine 3 specifically to create custom maps, mods and content for Crysis 2 is available on Crytek's website.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] Crytek also released a free-to-use version of the CryEngine for non-commercial game development.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] It was released as of August 17, 2011 under the name CRYENGINE® Free SDK.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] Crytek announced on September 9, 2011, that they would be using CryEngine 3 to bring the original *Crysis* to consoles.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] It was released for Xbox Live and PlayStation Network on October 4, 2011.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] On August 21, 2013, Crytek rebranded CryEngine (starting from version 3.6.0) to simply "CryEngine", and announced that their next CryEngine would not be advertised with a version number.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] The reason for this decision was the claim that this new engine bears almost no similarity to previous CryEngine versions.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] However, the development kits available to licensees still use version numbers.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] The new CryEngine version adds support for Linux and consoles such as the PlayStation 4, Xbox One, and Wii U.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] Subsequent appearances at events have also featured the use of CryEngine on virtual reality systems, at GDC 2015 Crytek brought a demonstration 'Back To Dinosaur Island' to the event to showcase such.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] On March 22, 2016, Crytek announced a new version of CryEngine, called CryEngine V.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] Additionally, a new licensing model was introduced with a "pay what you want" model for usage and access to the source code.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] On September 21, 2017, CryEngine 5.4 was released, adding the Vulkan API renderer as a beta, substance integration, and other features including new C# templates, asset system updates, and new anti-aliasing techniques.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] In December 2018, Crytek announced plans to integrate new cryptocurrency CryCash for purchases on the CryEngine Marketplace in Q2 2018.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] On March 20, 2018, Crytek changed the licensing from "pay what you want" to a 5% revenue-sharing model.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] In February 2022, Crytek announced to transform the CryEngine Marketplace into a free asset database.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] In April 2022, version 5.7 was released with few new features as the multiple features originally intended to be in 5.7 were scrapped and moved to the next iteration of CryEngine.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] Version 5.7 included Scaleform 4 support.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] The developers have stated that this will be the last version of CryEngine V and confirmed they are working on a new iteration of CryEngine.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] The previous versions prior to 5.7 were deprecated and can not be downloaded.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] The CryEngine software development kit (SDK), originally called Sandbox Editor, is the current version of the level editor used to create levels for CryEngine by Crytek.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] Tools are also provided within the software to facilitate scripting, animation, and object creation.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] It has been included with various Crytek games (including, but not limited to, *Crysis* and *Far Cry*), and is used extensively for modding purposes.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] The editing style is that of the sandbox concept, with the emphasis on large terrains and a free style of mission programming.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] The editor can also construct indoor settings.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] As opposed to editors like UnrealEd (Used in Unreal Engine 1, and Unreal Engine 2), which use a "subtractive" editing style that takes away areas from a filled world space, the Sandbox has an "additive" style (like *Quake II*).
[src:cryengine/cryengine] Objects are added to an overall empty space.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] The Sandbox's concentration on potentially huge (in theory, hundreds of square kilometers) terrain, means that it uses an algorithmic form of painting textures and objects onto the landscape.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] This uses various parameters to define the distribution of textures or types of vegetation.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] This is intended to save time and make the editing of such large terrains feasible while maintaining the overall "real world" sandbox-free roaming style.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] This is different from some editing styles that often use "fake backdrops" to give the illusion of large terrains.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] In a fashion somewhat comparable to the 3D Renderer Blender, which can be used for game design, the Sandbox editor has the ability, with a single key press, for the editor to jump straight into the current design (WYSIWYP, "What You See Is What You Play" Feature).
[src:cryengine/cryengine] This is facilitated without loading the game as the game engine is already running within the editor.
[src:cryengine/cryengine] The "player" view is shown within the 3D portion of the Editor.
[src:cryengine/crytek] Crytek's former studios included Crytek Black Sea in Sofia, Bulgaria, Crytek UK in Nottingham, and Crytek USA in Austin, Texas.
[src:cryengine/crytek] As of August 2024, Crytek is the largest game developer in Germany with 405 employees.
[src:cryengine/crytek] Crytek was founded by the Turkish-German brothers Cevat, Avni and Faruk Yerli in September 1999 in Coburg, Germany.
[src:cryengine/crytek] One of its first projects was a tech demo of a game called *X-Isle: Dinosaur Island*, which showcased its game engine technology that offered larger viewing distances than other game engines could at that time.
[src:cryengine/crytek] They met with Nvidia during the 1999 Electronic Entertainment Expo (E3) where its tech demo caught the attention of Nvidia and various media groups.
[src:cryengine/crytek] Crytek later signed on with Nvidia to distribute *X-Isle* as benchmarking software for Nvidia cards.
[src:cryengine/crytek] Crytek's first major game project was *Engalus*, a first-person shooter with a cyberpunk theme and role-playing elements, which was first privately shown at E3 2000.
[src:cryengine/crytek] The project first attracted publicity for the company at the 2000 ECTS with their tech demo at the Nvidia booth, but was subsequently cancelled.
[src:cryengine/crytek] Crytek was approached by Ubisoft to develop *X-Isle* into a full AAA game.
[src:cryengine/crytek] This evolved into *Far Cry*, which was released in March 2004.
[src:cryengine/crytek] Concurrently, Crytek announced its licensable game engine, CryEngine, that was used for *X-Isle* and *Far Cry*.
[src:cryengine/crytek] In February 2004, German police carried out a morning raid on Crytek offices, acting on an ex-intern's claim that Crytek was using software illegally.
[src:cryengine/crytek] The police investigated for software copies greater than licences purchased, but no charges were pressed.
[src:cryengine/crytek] That same month, Crytek and Electronic Arts (EA) announced a strategic partnership to develop a new gaming franchise based on the CryEngine, which would eventually be the *Crysis* series.
[src:cryengine/crytek] Crytek chose this path to highlight that the CryEngine was not limited to just what *Far Cry* had shown.
[src:cryengine/crytek] Due to this partnership, Ubisoft acquired the full rights to the *Far Cry* franchise by 2006 as well as a perpetual licence to the first CryEngine, which they have since adapted into their own Dunia Engine.
[src:cryengine/crytek] In December 2004, Crytek and ATI created a special cinematic machinima to demonstrate the future of PC gaming.
[src:cryengine/crytek] In January 2006, Crytek announced the development of *Crysis*, promising that it would be an original first-person shooter with a new kind of gameplay challenge requiring "adaptive tactics".
[src:cryengine/crytek] The game later won several Best PC Game awards from E3 and Games Convention.
[src:cryengine/crytek] In April 2006, Crytek moved to new offices in Frankfurt.
[src:cryengine/crytek] The first public demonstration of Crytek's CryEngine 2 was in January 2007, one year after *Crysis* was announced.
[src:cryengine/crytek] It has been licensed by many companies such as Avatar Reality, WeMade Entertainment, Entropia Universe, XLGames, Reloaded Studios.
[src:cryengine/crytek] On 11 May 2006, Crytek announced that its satellite studio in Kyiv, Ukraine, had been upgraded to a full development studio, giving the company its second development studio.
[src:cryengine/crytek] About a week after the upgrade of the Kyiv studio, Crytek announced a new studio in Budapest, Hungary.
[src:cryengine/crytek] On 14 July 2008, Crytek bought Black Sea Studios and renamed it to Crytek Black Sea.
[src:cryengine/crytek] On 17 November 2008, Crytek opened an office in South Korea named Crytek, Ltd.
[src:cryengine/crytek] On 3 February 2009, Crytek purchased Free Radical Design, a British video game company known for the *TimeSplitters* series, and renamed the company to Crytek UK.
[src:cryengine/crytek] In March 2009, Crytek announced on the company's website that it would introduce CryEngine 3 at the 2009 Game Developers Conference.
[src:cryengine/crytek] This new engine was developed for use on PlayStation 3, Xbox 360 and PCs.
[src:cryengine/crytek] In October 2009, CryEngine 3 became available in trade flow for game developers.
[src:cryengine/crytek] In March 2010, CryEngine 3 was made compatible with stereoscopic 3D technology.
[src:cryengine/crytek] Crytek released *Crysis 2*, a direct sequel to the original game, in March 2011.
[src:cryengine/crytek] At E3 2011, Crytek exhibited several new projects, including the action game *Ryse: Son of Rome*.
[src:cryengine/crytek] In September 2011, THQ and Crytek announced a partnership to develop *Homefront 2*.
[src:cryengine/crytek] After THQ filed for bankruptcy, Crytek acquired the *Homefront* franchise from THQ entirely in January 2013.
[src:cryengine/crytek] In February 2012, Crytek announced a new cloud based social gaming network called Gface.
[src:cryengine/crytek] The service is designed to help users meet people and play multiplayer video games with friends.
[src:cryengine/crytek] Crytek began researching a cloud gaming system in 2005 for *Crysis*, but paused development in 2007.
[src:cryengine/crytek] In April 2012, Crytek released the CryEngine 3.4 SDK which brought full DirectX 11 support to the CryEngine SDK.
[src:cryengine/crytek] Crytek released *Crysis 3* in February 2013 and *Ryse: Son of Rome* in November 2013 as an Xbox One launch title.
[src:cryengine/crytek] The PC version of *Ryse* was released in October 2014.
[src:cryengine/crytek] On 17 January 2013, Crytek officially opened an office in Istanbul, Turkey.
[src:cryengine/crytek] On 28 January 2013, Crytek opened a new studio, Crytek USA, in Austin, Texas, consisting primarily of former Vigil Games employees.
[src:cryengine/crytek] In June 2014, reports surfaced that Crytek had missed wage payments and withheld bonuses for Crytek UK and Crytek USA employees, and the company responded that it was in a "transitional phase" as it secured capital for future projects, with a particular emphasis on online gaming.
[src:cryengine/crytek] In July 2014, Crytek announced a strategic deal where the rights to *Homefront* including *Homefront: The Revolution* and the Crytek UK staff were transferred to Koch Media.
[src:cryengine/crytek] The team continued its work on the game as the new Deep Silver Dambuster Studios.
[src:cryengine/crytek] Crytek USA was restructured to remain an engine support team while development of *Hunt: Horrors of the Gilded Age* was transferred to Crytek.
[src:cryengine/crytek] Crytek announced the next iteration of the engine branded CRYENGINE V on 22 March 2016.
[src:cryengine/crytek] On 20 December 2016, Crytek announced that its studios in Hungary, Bulgaria, South Korea, Turkey and China would be shut down.
[src:cryengine/crytek] However, Crytek sold Crytek Black Sea to Sega and The Creative Assembly in March 2017 and stated to retained offices in Istanbul to operate Warface in Turkey in 2018.
[src:cryengine/crytek] In December 2017, Crytek announced a partnership with new cryptocurrency CryCash for use in rewarding gamers and esports betting; an initial coin offering was planned that month.
[src:cryengine/crytek] On 28 February 2018, Crytek announced that Cevat Yerli was stepping down as chief executive officer (CEO) of Crytek, with his brothers, Avni and Faruk Yerli, taking over the company's leadership as joint CEOs.
[src:cryengine/crytek] Cevat continues to support the company as an advisor and major shareholder.
[src:cryengine/crytek] Crytek released *Hunt: Showdown* (utilising the fifth generation of the CryEngine) in 2019–20.
[src:cryengine/crytek] The company has also worked on three virtual reality projects, namely *The Climb* for the Oculus Rift, *The Climb 2* for the Oculus Rift and Oculus Quest 2, and *Robinson: The Journey* for the PlayStation VR, Oculus Rift and SteamVR.
[src:cryengine/crytek] *Arena of Fate* was cancelled after Crytek's restructuring which saw the game's developer Crytek Black Sea sold.
[src:cryengine/crytek] In February 2019, *Warface*'s development team split from Crytek Kiev and formed Blackwood Games to continue working on the game.
[src:cryengine/crytek] In July 2021, German tabloid BILD reported that the Chinese Internet company Tencent was attempting to buy Crytek for over €300 million via a European subsidiary.
[src:cryengine/crytek] In 2021, the Creative Services team responsible for creating trailers won a Gold MUSE Award for The Dark Sight Trailer that promoted Hunt: Showdown.
[src:cryengine/crytek] On 26 January 2022 Crytek announced the fourth entry of the Crysis franchise, but the game was put on hold in 2025 followed by another round of layoffs.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] In the field of 3D computer graphics, **deferred shading** is a screen-space shading technique that is performed on a second rendering pass, after the vertex and pixel shaders are rendered.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] It was first suggested by Michael Deering in 1988.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] On the first pass of a deferred shader, only data that is required for shading computation is gathered.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] Positions, normals, and materials for each surface are rendered into the geometry buffer (G-buffer) using "render to texture".
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] After this, a pixel shader computes the direct and indirect lighting at each pixel using the information of the texture buffers in screen space.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] Screen space directional occlusion can be made part of the deferred shading pipeline to give directionality to shadows and interreflections.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] The primary advantage of deferred shading is the decoupling of scene geometry from lighting.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] Only one geometry pass is required, and each light is only computed for those pixels that it actually affects.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] This gives the ability to render many lights in a scene without a significant performance hit.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] There are some other advantages claimed for the approach.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] These include simpler management of complex lighting resources, ease of managing other complex shader resources, and the simplification of the software rendering pipeline.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] One key disadvantage of deferred rendering is the inability to handle transparency within the algorithm, although this problem is a generic one in Z-buffered scenes and it tends to be handled by delaying and sorting the rendering of transparent portions of the scene.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] Depth peeling can be used to achieve order-independent transparency in deferred rendering, but at the cost of additional batches and g-buffer size.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] Modern hardware, supporting DirectX 10 and later, is often capable of performing batches fast enough to maintain interactive frame rates.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] When order-independent transparency is desired (commonly for consumer applications) deferred shading is no less effective than forward shading using the same technique.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] Another serious disadvantage is the difficulty with using multiple materials.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] It's possible to use many different materials, but it requires more data to be stored in the G-buffer, which is already quite large and takes up a large amount of the memory bandwidth.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] One more disadvantage is that, due to separating the lighting stage from the geometric stage, hardware anti-aliasing does not produce correct results anymore since interpolated subsamples would result in nonsensical position, normal, and tangent attributes.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] Although it is not an edge-smoothing technique, temporal anti-aliasing (used in *Halo: Reach and Unreal Engine*) can also help give edges a smoother appearance.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] DirectX 10 introduced features allowing shaders to access individual samples in multi-sampled render targets (and depth buffers in version 10.1), giving users of this API access to hardware anti-aliasing in deferred shading.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] These features also allow them to correctly apply HDR luminance mapping to anti-aliased edges, where in earlier versions of the API any benefit of anti-aliasing may have been lost.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] Use of the technique has increased in video games because of the control it enables in terms of using a large amount of dynamic lights and reducing the complexity of required shader instructions.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] In comparison to deferred lighting, this technique is not very popular due to high memory size and bandwidth requirements, especially on seventh generation consoles where graphic memory size and bandwidth are limited and often bottlenecks.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] The idea of deferred shading was originally introduced by Michael Deering and his colleagues in a paper published in 1988 titled *The triangle processor and normal vector shader: a VLSI system for high performance graphics*.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] Although the paper never uses the word "deferred", a key concept is introduced; each pixel is shaded only once after depth resolution.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] Deferred shading as we know it today, using G-buffers, was introduced in a paper by Saito and Takahashi in 1990, although they too do not use the word "deferred".
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] The first deferred shaded video game was *Shrek*, an Xbox launch title shipped in 2001.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] Around 2004, implementations on commodity graphics hardware started to appear.
[src:cryengine/deferred-shading] The technique later gained popularity for applications such as video games, finally becoming mainstream around 2008 to 2010.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] The game was the first to use Crytek's CryEngine, and was designed as an open-ended first-person shooter, though it lacks most of the freedom its successors would offer to the player.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] While players can freely explore the game's world like in later *Far Cry* titles, they are most often discouraged from doing so due to the linear structure of missions and the lack of side content.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Despite this, the gameplay formula established in *Far Cry*—placing the player in a foreign environment occupied by enemy forces where they must use various weapons and tools, as well as their surroundings to overcome any threat—would prove essential in defining the series' identity going forward.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] The environment includes land, water, indoor and outdoor structures, all during various times of the day.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] The player has the ability to jump, run, crouch and lie down, and look about in all directions.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Sound plays an important part in the overall gameplay.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] For example, the general location of enemies can often be identified by hearing their footsteps or conversations.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Throughout the game, the player encounters a variety of weapons from which to choose, including automatic weapons and grenades.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] The open maps allow the player to complete their objectives in several different manners.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] When outdoors, the player is usually presented with a fairly simple set of possible routes to their objective, but these do not necessarily have to be used.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Outdoor map level designs are constructed in a way that allows the player to try different angles for assaults, or even completely circumvent enemies (given enough time to maneuver).
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] However, during the indoor sections of the game, level design tends to lose this attribute in favor of a more traditional, linear gameplay.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] The game included three multiplayer modes: Deathmatch, Team Deathmatch, and 'Assault' - An attack/defend mode where one team must guard three bases and the other must capture them.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Ubisoft closed the online servers in October 2015.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Army Special Forces soldier stranded on a mysterious archipelago.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] He is searching for a female journalist named Valerie Constantine, after she went missing when their boat was destroyed by mercenaries.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] The game includes thematic elements relating to the dangers of weaponizing genetic engineering and the genocide of local islanders as can be seen by the deformed creatures created by a mad scientist named Krieger.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] The terrain in *Far Cry* varies greatly.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Set on a South Pacific archipelago, the landscape includes beaches, dense rain forests, towering canyons, mines, swamps, and even volcanic forests.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Many of the interiors range from simple beach huts and army camps to elaborate complexes, an underground temple, and ultra-modern research labs.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Several of these mazes use the remains of Japanese World War II-era fortifications and bunkers.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Jack Carver has left his mysterious and bitter past behind him and dropped out of society to run a boat-charter business in the South Pacific.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] He is hired by a female journalist named Valerie Constantine to take her secretly to an uncharted island in Micronesia.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] After Val takes off on her own with a jet ski, Jack's boat is blown apart by a rocket, but he survives by diving into the water.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] With the help of a man named Doyle, Jack travels across the various islands, battling mysterious mercenaries in search for Val.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Through encounters with Trigens (genetically altered beasts) and information from Doyle, Jack soon discovers that the island is part of an experiment involving genetic modification, funded by the genetic company Krieger Corp. and led by its CEO, Dr.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] As the game progresses, it becomes clear that the Trigens, who are running loose, are becoming too large a problem for the mercenaries to handle, and that the experiments are not limited to just primate mutations, but have moved on to mutating humans (possibly mercenaries).
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] When Jack finally catches up with Val, she is being taken to another area by a helicopter which is stopped by Jack.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] After a brief struggle on board the helicopter, Val tells Jack to jump for it, kicking him in the face and they both fall from the helicopter as it explodes.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] After they both swim to shore, Val reveals that she is an undercover CIA agent investigating Krieger's operations.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] After further exploration, Jack must again search for and rescue Val while the human Trigens have escaped (freed by Jack) and have begun a revolt against the mercenaries on the island.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] After rescuing Val, they split up again and reunite when Jack has killed the mercenary commander, Crowe.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Information Crowe had with him indicates Krieger has a tactical nuke on the island, which he intends to use as a last resort in covering his tracks should his projects be investigated.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] After the Department of Defense has supposedly analyzed the situation, Jack and Val steal the nuclear weapon, despite Jack's protests.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Before entering the factory, Doyle warns that the mutagen might infect them when the blast goes off, and advises them to take a mutagen-resistant serum before arming the nuke.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Inside the factory, they do so and arm the nuke, which detonates directly behind Jack and Val as they exit the factory, leaving them unconscious.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] While the pair are unconscious, Krieger captures them before leaving to his main base in a helicopter.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Jack, kicked off the helicopter, has to fight through the Trigen-infested area to rescue Val and escape the islands with his life.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Upon reaching a mercenary weapons cache, Jack notices his arm is turning green.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Doyle responds that the mutagen concentration on the air might be too strong for the antidote, but Krieger is working on a cure in a laboratory nearby.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Jack is thus directed to find Krieger, who has injected himself with the mutagen but is ultimately defeated.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] With his dying breath, Krieger reveals that there is no cure for the mutagen.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Doyle reveals the "antidote" they took earlier was the very mutagen they were trying to protect themselves from and reveals that he plans to sell the mutagen formula on the black market before fleeing.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] After battling through a horde of Trigens, Jack catches up with Doyle and kills him.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Jack then escapes just before the volcano, in which Krieger's main offices are located, erupts.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Both he and Val are cured from the mutagen and manage to sail off on a boat.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Crytek developed a game engine called CryEngine for *Far Cry*.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Reportedly, the game was born out of a technology demo called *X-Isle: Dinosaur Island* made by Crytek to showcase the capabilities of the Nvidia GeForce 3.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] On June 10, 2013, Ubisoft announced *Far Cry Classic* would come to XBLA as part of Microsoft's 2013 Summer Arcade releases.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] The game was delayed to February 12, 2014.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] *Far Cry Classic* is an HD remake for PlayStation 3 and Xbox 360.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] The game is available as a standalone and part of a compilation called *Far Cry: The Wild Expedition*.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] In June 2023, the game's source code was leaked online.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] On April 8, 2004, Ubisoft announced *Far Cry Instincts* for the Xbox.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] *Far Cry Instincts* is not a direct port of the original, being designed specifically for consoles.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] The game uses a similar premise to the original PC version, and the same game engine, but by comparison *Instincts* is less open-ended and more linear, due to the console's reduced processing power which prevents the full rendering of the PC version's vast islands and landscape.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Additionally, *Instincts* features a significantly altered storyline, and new multiplayer modes, weapons, dual wielding and "feral abilities".
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] PlayStation 2 and GameCube were also planned but were cancelled.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] *Far Cry Instincts* was exclusive to the Xbox and was released to acclaim in North America on September 27, 2005.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] On March 28, 2006, Ubisoft released a sequel to *Instincts*, *Far Cry Instincts: Evolution* for the Xbox, which was met with less enthusiasm than the first versions of *Far Cry*.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] On the same day, for the Xbox 360, *Far Cry Instincts: Predator* was released, which essentially contains updated versions of *Instincts* and *Evolution* that can run in 720p or 1080i high-definition.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] *Evolution* includes a new single-player campaign, although it is considerably shorter than that of *Far Cry Instincts*.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] The storyline focuses on Jack Carver's work for a woman named Kade, which leads him to be hunted by local governments due to a frame-up during a botched arms deal.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Jack again meets up with Doyle, who is practicing damage control, and eventually must battle a native warrior named Semeru who possesses the same "feral abilities" as Jack.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] A remake of *Far Cry Instincts: Evolution*, titled *Far Cry Vengeance*, was released as part of Ubisoft's launch lineup for the Wii.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] In this version, the Wii Remote is used for many of the tasks assigned to buttons in previous iterations of the game, including driving vehicles, shooting, and running.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Crytek was commissioned by Electronic Arts to continue development on the Crytek engine, which led to their series of games, *Crysis*.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] As Crytek was locked into its contract with Electronic Arts, Ubisoft negotiated to hold the rights to *Far Cry* as well as a perpetual license for the CryEngine, which they continued to modify with their Dunia Engine.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] In 2008, *Far Cry 2* was released, developed by Ubisoft Montreal.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] *Far Cry 2* centers around the activities of a gun smuggler named The Jackal.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Fan theories, based on the appearance of the Jackal as well as game files, claim that the Jackal was an aged Jack Carver.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] *Far Cry 2*'s director, Clint Hocking, confirmed this was intentional in a 2021 interview, with the trauma of events of *Far Cry* leading Carver to turn to criminal smuggling ten years later.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] Several more *Far Cry* sequels have been released by Ubisoft since.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] On October 2, 2008, a live-action film based on the video game was released in Germany and later on December 17, 2008, in American theaters, receiving overwhelmingly negative reviews.
[src:cryengine/far-cry-video-game] A reboot was planned in 2013, and later adapted into a Netflix series instead.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] A **game engine** is a software framework primarily designed for video game development, which may include specialized software libraries and packages, such as level editors.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] The term "engine" is a direct analogue of "software engine", having it employed across sectors of the software industry.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Furthermore, *game engine* may also refer to the integrated development environment as an interface behind the given framework, typically a suite of visual development tools and features for developing video games.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Game developers can use game engines to create and publish video games across platforms, such as desktops, mobile devices, video game consoles, and other types of computers.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] The core functionalities commonly covered by a game engine are a 2D or 3D renderer, physics engine, audio engine, scripting, animation, artificial intelligence, networking, streaming, memory management, threads, localization support, scene graph, and cinematics.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Game engine developers often economize game development through reuse or adaptation of abstractions built into game engines for production of various games, or through porting of videogames from a single to other target platforms.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] In many cases, game engines provide a suite of visual development tools in addition to reusable software components.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] These tools are generally provided in an integrated development environment to enable simplified, rapid development of games in a data-driven manner.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Game-engine developers often attempt to preempt implementer needs by developing robust software suites, which include many elements a game developer may need to build a game.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Most game-engine suites provide facilities that ease development, such as graphics, sound, physics and artificial intelligence (AI) functions.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Like other types of middleware, game engines usually provide platform abstraction, allowing the same game to run on various platforms (including game consoles and personal computers) with few, if any, changes made to the game source code.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Often, programmers design game engines with a component-based architecture that allows specific systems in the engine to be replaced or extended with more specialized (and often more expensive) game-middleware components.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Some game engines comprise a series of loosely-connected game middleware components that can be selectively combined to create a custom engine, instead of the more common approach of extending or customizing a flexible integrated product.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] However achieved, extensibility remains a high priority for game engines due to the wide variety of uses for which they are applied.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Despite the specificity of the name "game engine", end users often re-purpose game engines for other kinds of interactive applications with real-time graphical requirements—such as marketing demos, architectural visualizations, training simulations, and modeling environments.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Some game engines only provide real-time 3D rendering capabilities instead of the wide range of functionality needed by games.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] These engines rely upon the game developer to implement the rest of this functionality or to assemble it from other game-middleware components.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] These types of engines are generally referred to as a "graphics engine", "rendering engine", or "3D engine" instead of the all-encompassing term "game engine".
[src:cryengine/game-engine] This terminology is inconsistently used, as many full-featured 3D game engines are simply referred to as "3D engines".
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Examples of graphics engines include: Crystal Space, Genesis3D, Irrlicht, OGRE, RealmForge, Truevision3D, and Vision Engine.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Modern game- or graphics-engines generally provide a scene graph—an object-oriented representation of the 3D game-world which often simplifies game design and can be used for more efficient rendering of vast virtual worlds.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Most game engines or graphics engines use a Graphics API, which eases communication with the GPU.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] But older games did not have hardware acceleration or GPUs and had to build their own software renderer.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] As technology ages, the components of an engine may become obsolete or insufficient for the requirements of a given project.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Since the complexity of programming an entirely new engine may result in unwanted delays (or necessitate that a project restart from the beginning), an engine-development team may elect to update their existing engine with newer functionality or components.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Game engines are not limited to use in the video game field, and have found uses in other scientific fields.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Part of this is due to game engines being optimized for consumer-grade computing equipment rather than high-performance computing, allowing researchers to develop programs for their use on lower cost machines.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Game engines also simplify many of the computing operations needed for scientific software, including graphics, networking, and interactivity, reducing the need to develop these features themselves.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Before game engines, games were typically written as singular entities: a game for the Atari 2600, for example, had to be designed from the bottom up to make optimal use of the display hardware—this core display routine is now called the kernel by developers of games for older systems.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Other platforms had more leeway, but even when display was not a concern, memory constraints usually sabotaged attempts to create the data-heavy design that an engine needs.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Even on more accommodating platforms, very little could be reused between games.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] The rapid advance of arcade hardware—which was the leading edge of the market at the time—meant that most of the code would have to be thrown out afterwards anyway, as later generations of games would use completely different game designs that took advantage of extra resources.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Thus, most game designs through the 1980s were designed through a hard-coded rule set with a small number of levels and graphics data.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Since the golden age of arcade video games, it became common for video game companies to develop in-house game engines for use with first-party software.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] A notable example of an in-house game engine on home consoles in the mid-1980s was the smooth side-scrolling engine developed by Shigeru Miyamoto's team at Nintendo for the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES).
[src:cryengine/game-engine] The engine they had developed for the side-scrolling racing game *Excitebike* (1984) was later employed for the scrolling platformer *Super Mario Bros.* (1985).
[src:cryengine/game-engine] This allowed Mario to smoothly accelerate from a walk to a run, rather than move at a constant speed like in earlier platformers.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] While third-party game engines were not common until the rise of 3D computer graphics in the 1990s, several 2D game creation systems were produced in the 1980s for independent video game development.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Klik & Play (1994) is another legacy offering that is still available.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] The term *game engine* emerged in the mid-1990s, particularly with the rise of 3D games like first-person shooters, which often featured a dedicated first-person shooter engine.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] For instance, Epic Games, founded by Tim Sweeney, debuted its Unreal Engine in 1998.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Later games, such as id Software's *Quake III Arena* and Epic Games' *Unreal* (1998), were designed with this approach in mind, with the engine and content developed separately.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] At the very least, reusable engines make developing game sequels faster and easier, which is a valuable advantage in the competitive video game industry.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] While a strong rivalry existed between Epic Games and id Software around 2000, Epic Game's Unreal Engine has since become far more popular than id Tech 4 and its successor, id Tech 5.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Modern game engines are some of the most complex applications written, often featuring dozens of finely-tuned systems interacting to ensure a precisely-controlled user experience.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] The continued evolution of game engines has created a strong separation between rendering, scripting, artwork, and level design.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] As such, it is now common, for example, for a typical game development team to have several times as many artists as actual programmers.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] While third-party game engines are predominantly used in the development of first-person shooter games, they are also being used across other genres.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] For example, Gamebryo is used in *The Elder Scrolls III: Morrowind* and *Dark Age of Camelot*, whereas Unreal Engine 2 is used in *Lineage II*.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Game engines are also used for games originally developed for home consoles, with RenderWare for the *Grand Theft Auto* and *Burnout* franchises as an example.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Due to modern multi-core systems and growing demands in realism, exploiting threads has become more important.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Separate threads of execution within a game engine manage intensive operations, including rendering, asset streaming, audio playback, and physics simulation.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Racing games have typically been at the forefront of threading with the physics engine running in a separate thread long before other core subsystems were moved, partly because rendering and related tasks need updating at only 30–60 Hz.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] For example, on PlayStation 3, physics ran in *Need For Speed* at 100 Hz, versus *Forza Motorsport 2* at 360 Hz.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Although the term was first used in the 1990s, few earlier systems in 1980s are considered as game engines, such as Sierra's Adventure Game Interpreter (AGI) and SCI systems, LucasArts' SCUMM system and Incentive Software's Freescape engine (in 1986).
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Unlike most modern game engines, these game engines were never used in any third-party products (except for the SCUMM system, which was licensed to and used by Humongous Entertainment).
[src:cryengine/game-engine] As game engine technology matures and becomes more user friendly, the application of game engines has widened in scope.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] They are now used for serious games: visualization, training, medical, and military simulation applications, with the CryEngine being one example.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] To improve accessibility, new hardware platforms are also now targeted by game engines, including mobile phones (e.g.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Additionally, more game engines are being built upon higher-level languages, such as Java, C# and .NET (e.g., TorqueX, and Visual3D.NET), Python (Panda3D), or Lua Script (Leadwerks).
[src:cryengine/game-engine] As most 3D-rich games are now mostly limited by the power of a graphics card, the potential slowdown due to translation overheads of higher-level languages becomes negligible, while productivity gains offered by these languages serve the game engine developers' benefit.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] These recent trends are being propelled by companies such as Microsoft to support indie game development.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Microsoft developed XNA as the primary Software Development Kit (SDK) for all video games released on Xbox and their related products.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] This includes the Xbox Live Indie Games channel designed specifically for smaller developers who do not have the extensive resources necessary to box games for sale on retail shelves.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] It is becoming easier and cheaper than ever to develop game engines for platforms that support managed frameworks.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Producers of game engines decide how they allow users to use their products.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Just as gaming is an industry, so are the engines they are built off.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] The major game engines come at varying prices, whether it be in the form of subscription fees or license payments.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Unity and Unreal Engine are currently the two most popular choices for game developers.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Although the differences among the different game engines blur as they build their own tools on top of them, different game developers may be too used to a system to change, or attracted by the huge benefits of such engines regardless of pay-walls.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Free and open-source engines such as Godot, have seen a rise in popularity, particularly following the 2023 Unity pricing controversy which drove game developers and studios to seek engines with a permissive license.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Applied more broadly, game engines themselves can be described as middleware.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] In video games, however, *middleware* is often used to refer to subsystems of functionality within a game engine.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Some game middleware does only one thing, yet does it more convincingly or more efficiently than general purpose middleware.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] The four most-widely used middleware packages that provide subsystems of functionality include RAD Game Tools' Bink, Firelight FMOD, Havok, and Scaleform GFx.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] RAD Game Tools develops Bink for basic video rendering, along with Miles audio, and Granny 3D rendering.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Firelight FMOD is a low cost robust audio library and toolset.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Havok provides a robust physics simulation system, along with a suite of animation and behavior applications.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Scaleform provides GFx for high performance Flash UI and high-quality video playback, and an Input Method Editor (IME) addon for in-game Asian chat support.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Other middleware is used for performance optimization—for example Simplygon helps to optimize and generate level of detail meshes, and Umbra adds occlusion culling optimizations to 3D graphics.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Some middleware contains full source code, or is provided an API reference for a compiled binary library.
[src:cryengine/game-engine] Some middleware programs can be licensed either way, usually for a higher fee for full source code.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In a computer graphics context, in standard usage, the word "rendering" by itself means rendering 3D scenes, but it is sometimes used with a broader meaning.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A modifier such as "2D" or "3D" is used when there is potential ambiguity (e.g.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A software application or component that performs rendering is called a **rendering engine**, **render engine**, **rendering system**, **graphics engine**, or simply a **renderer**.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A distinction is made between real-time rendering, in which images are generated and displayed immediately (ideally fast enough to give the impression of motion or animation), and offline rendering (sometimes called pre-rendering) in which images or film frames, are generated for later viewing.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Offline rendering can use a slower and higher-quality renderer.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Interactive applications such as games must primarily use real-time rendering, although they may incorporate pre-rendered content.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering produces images of scenes or objects defined using coordinates in 3D space, seen from a particular viewpoint.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It uses knowledge and ideas from optics, the study of visual perception, mathematics, and software engineering, and it has applications such as video games, simulators, visual effects for films and television, design visualization, and medical diagnosis.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering requires modeling the propagation of light in an environment, e.g. by applying the rendering equation.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Real-time rendering uses high-performance *rasterization* algorithms that process a list of shapes and determine which pixels are covered by each shape.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When more realism is required (e.g. for architectural visualization or visual effects) slower pixel-by-pixel algorithms such as *ray tracing* are used instead.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (Ray tracing can also be used selectively during rasterized rendering to improve the realism of lighting and reflections.) A type of ray tracing called *path tracing* is currently the most common technique for photorealistic rendering.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Path tracing is also popular for generating high-quality non-photorealistic images, such as frames for 3D animated films.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Both rasterization and ray tracing can be sped up ("accelerated") by specially designed microprocessors called GPUs.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rasterization algorithms are also used to produce images containing only 2D shapes such as polygons and text.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] This type of rendering is sometimes called *2D rendering*, and its applications include digital illustration, graphic design, 2D animation, desktop publishing and the display of user interfaces.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, rendering was called **image synthesis** but today this term is likely to mean AI image generation.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The term "neural rendering" is sometimes used when a neural network is the primary means of generating an image but some degree of control over the output image is provided.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks can also assist rendering without replacing traditional algorithms, e.g. by removing noise from path traced images.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A large proportion of computer graphics research has worked towards producing images that resemble photographs.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Fundamental techniques that make this possible were invented in the 1980s, but at the end of the decade, photorealism for complex scenes was still considered a distant goal.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Today, photorealism is routinely achievable for offline rendering, but remains difficult for real-time rendering.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In order to produce realistic images, rendering must simulate how light travels from light sources, is reflected, refracted, and scattered (often many times) by objects in the scene, passes through a camera lens, and finally reaches the film or sensor of the camera.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The physics used in these simulations is primarily geometrical optics, in which particles of light follow (usually straight) lines called *rays*, but in some situations (such as when rendering thin films, like the surface of soap bubbles) the wave nature of light must be taken into account.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In realistic scenes, objects are illuminated both by light that arrives directly from a light source (after passing mostly unimpeded through air), and light that has bounced off other objects in the scene.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The simulation of this complex lighting is called global illumination.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In the past, indirect lighting was often faked (especially when rendering animated films) by placing additional hidden lights in the scene, but today path tracing is used to render it accurately.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For true photorealism, the camera used to take the photograph must be simulated.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The *thin lens approximation* allows combining perspective projection with depth of field (and bokeh) emulation.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Camera lens simulations can be made more realistic by modeling the way light is refracted by the components of the lens.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Motion blur is often simulated if film or video frames are being rendered.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Simulated lens flare and bloom are sometimes added to make the image appear subjectively brighter (although the design of real cameras tries to reduce these effects).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering uses mathematical descriptions of how different surface materials reflect light, called *reflectance models* or (when physically plausible) *bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs)*.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering materials such as marble, plant leaves, and human skin requires simulating an effect called subsurface scattering, in which a portion of the light travels into the material, is scattered, and then travels back out again.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The way color, and properties such as roughness, vary over a surface can be represented efficiently using texture mapping.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For some applications (including early stages of 3D modeling), simplified rendering styles such as wireframe rendering may be appropriate, particularly when the material and surface details have not been defined and only the shape of an object is known.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Games and other real-time applications may use simpler and less realistic rendering techniques as an artistic or design choice, or to allow higher frame rates on lower-end hardware.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Orthographic and isometric projections can be used for a stylized effect or to ensure that parallel lines are depicted as parallel in CAD rendering.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Non-photorealistic rendering (NPR) uses techniques like edge detection and posterization to produce 3D images that resemble technical illustrations, cartoons, or other styles of drawing or painting.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In 2D computer graphics the positions and sizes of shapes are specified using 2D coordinates (x and y) instead of 3D coordinates (x, y, and z).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering APIs often use a resolution-independent coordinate system, with a viewport determining how to convert coordinates to pixel indexes called *device coordinates*.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transformations such as scaling, translation, and rotation may be applied before rendering the shapes.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These affine transformations are often represented by 3 × 3 matrices, allowing easier composition of transformations.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Higher-quality 2D rendering engines such as SVG renderers usually implement anti-aliasing to reduce the jagged appearance of rasterized lines and shape edges.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering overlapping shapes, renderers commonly use a "painter's model" in which the shapes are drawn in some determined order, or their contributions to each pixel are composited using blending operations that may depend on the order of the inputs.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers may allow giving shapes a "z index" or "stacking order" to specify the rendering or blending order (unlike the z coordinate used in 3D rendering, this third coordinate only indicates an order, not a distance, and cannot be meaningfully rotated together with the x and y coordinates).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering typically does not simulate light propagation (which would likely require specifying 3D positions or thickness for the shapes).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Effects such as drop shadows and transparency are defined by mathematical functions with no physical basis.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering for print output may need to support very high resolutions, e.g.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 600 or 1200 DPI for a typical laser printer, or 2400 DPI or higher for an imagesetter or platesetter.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Grayscale and color images require halftones (or some form of dithering or stochastic screening) and color separations.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A rendering engine called a *raster image processor* (RIP) converts input data such as PDF files into the high-resolution bitmap images used by the printer.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before a 3D scene or 2D image can be rendered, it must be described in a way that the rendering software can understand.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, inputs for both 2D and 3D rendering were usually text files, which are easier than binary files for humans to edit and debug.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Traditional rendering algorithms use geometric descriptions of 3D scenes or 2D images.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Applications and algorithms that render visualizations of data scanned from the real world, or scientific simulations, may require different types of input data.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The PostScript format (which is often credited with the rise of desktop publishing) provides a standardized, interoperable way to describe 2D graphics and page layout.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) format is also text-based, and the PDF format uses the PostScript language internally.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Many file formats exist for storing individual 3D objects or "models".
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These can be imported into a larger scene, or loaded on-demand by rendering software or games.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A realistic scene may require hundreds of items like household objects, vehicles, and trees, and 3D artists often utilize large libraries of models.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In game production, these models (along with other data such as textures, audio files, and animations) are referred to as "assets".
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scientific and engineering visualization often requires rendering volumetric data generated by 3D scans or simulations.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Perhaps the most common source of such data is medical CT and MRI scans, which need to be rendered for diagnosis.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Volumetric data can be extremely large, and requires specialized data formats to store it efficiently, particularly if the volume is *sparse* (with empty regions that do not contain data).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before rendering, level sets for volumetric data can be extracted and converted into a mesh of triangles, e.g. by using the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms have also been developed that work directly with volumetric data, for example to render realistic depictions of the way light is scattered and absorbed by clouds and smoke, and this type of volumetric rendering is used extensively in visual effects for movies.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering lower-resolution volumetric data without interpolation, the individual cubes or "voxels" may be visible, an effect sometimes used deliberately for game graphics.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photographs of real world objects can be incorporated into a rendered scene by using them as textures for 3D objects.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photos of a scene can also be stitched together to create panoramic images or environment maps, which allow the scene to be rendered very efficiently but only from a single viewpoint.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scanning of real objects and scenes using structured light or lidar produces point clouds consisting of the coordinates of millions of individual points in space, sometimes along with color information.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These point clouds may either be rendered directly or converted into meshes before rendering.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A more recent, experimental approach is description of scenes using radiance fields which define the color, intensity, and direction of incoming light at each point in space.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (This is conceptually similar to, but not identical to, the light field recorded by a hologram.) For any useful resolution, the amount of data in a radiance field is so large that it is impractical to represent it directly as volumetric data, and an approximation function must be found.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks are typically used to generate and evaluate these approximations, sometimes using video frames, or a collection of photographs of a scene taken at different angles, as "training data".
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms related to neural networks have recently been used to find approximations of a scene as 3D Gaussians.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The resulting representation is similar to a point cloud, except that it uses fuzzy, partially-transparent blobs of varying dimensions and orientations instead of points.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] As with neural radiance fields, these approximations are often generated from photographs or video frames.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of rendering may be displayed immediately on the screen (many times a second, in the case of real-time rendering such as games) or saved in a raster graphics file format such as JPEG or PNG.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] High-end rendering applications commonly use the OpenEXR file format, which can represent finer gradations of colors and high dynamic range lighting, allowing tone mapping or other adjustments to be applied afterwards without loss of quality.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of a renderer sometimes includes more than just RGB color values.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transparency information can be included, allowing rendered foreground objects to be composited with photographs or video.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It is also sometimes useful to store the contributions of different lights, or of specular and diffuse lighting, as separate channels, so lighting can be adjusted after rendering.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The OpenEXR format allows storing many channels of data in a single file.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers such as Blender and Pixar RenderMan support a large variety of configurable values called Arbitrary Output Variables (AOVs).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Choosing how to render a 3D scene usually involves trade-offs between speed, memory usage, and realism (although realism is not always desired).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The **algorithms** developed over the years follow a loose progression, with more advanced methods becoming practical as computing power and memory capacity increased.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Multiple techniques may be used for a single final image.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important distinction is between image order algorithms, which iterate over pixels in the image, and object order algorithms, which iterate over objects in the scene.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For simple scenes, object order is usually more efficient, as there are fewer objects than pixels.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] algorithms that also support filled shapes.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In principle, any 2D vector graphics renderer can be used to render 3D objects by first projecting them onto a 2D image plane.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Different realistic or stylized effects can be obtained by coloring the pixels covered by the objects in different ways.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization is usually synonymous with "object order" rendering (as described above).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It can be used to implement "image order" rendering by casting a ray for each pixel, and finding a corresponding point in the scene.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , requiring a varying number of ray casting operations for each path.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] is usually in the domain of path tracing.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] approach that breaks surfaces in the scene into pieces, and estimates the amount of light that each piece receives from light sources, or indirectly from other surfaces.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] of each surface is known, the scene can be rendered using rasterization or ray tracing.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , giving ray tracing a rigorous mathematical foundation.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Each of the above approaches has many variations, and there is some overlap.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing may be considered either a distinct technique or a particular type of ray tracing.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that the usage of terminology related to ray tracing and path tracing has changed significantly over time.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray marching is a family of algorithms, used by ray casting, for finding intersections between a ray and a complex object, such as a volumetric dataset or a surface defined by a signed distance function.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It is not, by itself, a rendering method, but it can be incorporated into ray tracing and path tracing, and is used by rasterization to implement screen-space reflection and other effects.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A technique called photon mapping traces paths of photons from a light source to an object, accumulating data about irradiance which is then used during conventional ray tracing or path tracing.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering a scene using only rays traced from the light source to the camera is impractical, even though it corresponds more closely to reality, because a huge number of photons would need to be simulated, only a tiny fraction of which actually hit the camera.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Some authors call conventional ray tracing "backward" ray tracing because it traces the paths of photons backwards from the camera to the light source, and call following paths from the light source (as in photon mapping) "forward" ray tracing.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, sometimes the meaning of these terms is reversed.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Tracing rays starting at the light source can also be called *particle tracing* or *light tracing*, which avoids this ambiguity.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real-time rendering, including video game graphics, typically uses rasterization, but increasingly combines it with ray tracing and path tracing.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To enable realistic global illumination, real-time rendering often relies on pre-rendered ("baked") lighting for stationary objects.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For moving objects, it may use a technique called *light probes*, in which lighting is recorded by rendering omnidirectional views of the scene at chosen points in space (often points on a grid to allow easier interpolation).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These are similar to environment maps, but typically use a very low resolution or an approximation such as spherical harmonics.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The term *rasterization* (in a broad sense) encompasses many techniques used for 2D rendering and real-time 3D rendering.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] 3D animated films were rendered by rasterization before ray tracing and path tracing became practical.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A renderer combines rasterization with *geometry processing* (which is not specific to rasterization) and *pixel processing* which computes the RGB color values to be placed in the *framebuffer* for display.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, 3D rasterization used algorithms like the *Warnock algorithm* and *scanline rendering* (also called "scan-conversion"), which can handle arbitrary polygons and can rasterize many shapes simultaneously.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Although such algorithms are still important for 2D rendering, 3D rendering now usually divides shapes into triangles and rasterizes them individually using simpler methods.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] High-performance algorithms exist for rasterizing 2D lines, including anti-aliased lines, as well as ellipses and filled triangles.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important special case of 2D rasterization is text rendering, which requires careful anti-aliasing and rounding of coordinates to avoid distorting the letterforms and preserve spacing, density, and sharpness.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After 3D coordinates have been projected onto the image plane, rasterization is primarily a 2D problem, but the 3rd dimension necessitates *hidden surface removal*.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early computer graphics used geometric algorithms or ray casting to remove the hidden portions of shapes, or used the *painter's algorithm*, which sorts shapes by depth (distance from camera) and renders them from back to front.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Depth sorting was later avoided by incorporating depth comparison into the scanline rendering algorithm.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The *z-buffer* algorithm performs the comparisons indirectly by including a depth or "z" value in the framebuffer.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A pixel is only covered by a shape if that shape's z value is lower (indicating closer to the camera) than the z value currently in the buffer.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The z-buffer requires additional memory (an expensive resource at the time it was invented) but simplifies the rasterization code and permits multiple passes.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Memory is now faster and more plentiful, and a z-buffer is almost always used for real-time rendering.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A drawback of the basic z-buffer algorithm is that each pixel ends up either entirely covered by a single object or filled with the background color, causing jagged edges in the final image.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early *anti-aliasing* approaches addressed this by detecting when a pixel is partially covered by a shape, and calculating the covered area.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The A-buffer (and other supersampling and multi-sampling techniques) solve the problem less precisely but with higher performance.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time 3D graphics, it has become common to use complicated heuristics (and even neural-networks) to perform anti-aliasing.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In 3D rasterization, color is usually determined by a *pixel shader* or *fragment shader*, a small program that is run for each pixel.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Until relatively recently, Pixar used rasterization for rendering its animated films.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Unlike the renderers commonly used for real-time graphics, the Reyes rendering system in Pixar's RenderMan software was optimized for rendering very small (pixel-sized) polygons, and incorporated stochastic sampling techniques more typically associated with ray tracing.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the simplest ways to render a 3D scene is to test if a ray starting at the viewpoint (the "eye" or "camera") intersects any of the geometric shapes in the scene, repeating this test using a different ray direction for each pixel.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This method, called *ray casting*, was important in early computer graphics, and is a fundamental building block for more advanced algorithms.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render shapes defined by *constructive solid geometry* (CSG) operations.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early ray casting experiments include the work of Arthur Appel in the 1960s.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Appel rendered shadows by casting an additional ray from each visible surface point towards a light source.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] He also tried rendering the density of illumination by casting random rays from the light source towards the object and plotting the intersection points (similar to the later technique called *photon mapping*).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When rendering scenes containing many objects, testing the intersection of a ray with every object becomes very expensive.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Special data structures are used to speed up this process by allowing large numbers of objects to be excluded quickly (such as objects behind the camera).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These structures are analogous to database indexes for finding the relevant objects.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The most common are the *bounding volume hierarchy* (BVH), which stores a pre-computed bounding box or sphere for each branch of a tree of objects, and the *k-d tree* which recursively divides space into two parts.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs include hardware acceleration for BVH intersection tests.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] K-d trees are a special case of *binary space partitioning*, which was frequently used in early computer graphics (it can also generate a rasterization order for the painter's algorithm).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Octrees*, another historically popular technique, are still often used for volumetric data.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Geometric formulas are sufficient for finding the intersection of a ray with shapes like spheres, polygons, and polyhedra, but for most curved surfaces there is no analytic solution, or the intersection is difficult to compute accurately using limited precision floating point numbers.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Root-finding algorithms such as Newton's method can sometimes be used.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To avoid these complications, curved surfaces are often approximated as meshes of triangles.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Volume rendering (e.g. rendering clouds and smoke), and some surfaces such as fractals, may require ray marching instead of basic ray casting.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render an image by tracing light rays backwards from a simulated camera.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After finding a point on a surface where a ray originated, another ray is traced towards the light source to determine if anything is casting a shadow on that point.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If there are multiple light sources, brightness contributions of the lights are added together.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For color images, calculations are repeated for multiple wavelengths of light (e.g. red, green, and blue).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing usually performs anti-aliasing by taking the average of multiple samples for each pixel.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It may also use multiple samples for effects like depth of field and motion blur.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If evenly spaced ray directions or times are used for each of these features, many rays are required, and some aliasing will remain.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Cook-style*, *stochastic*, or *Monte Carlo ray tracing* avoids this problem by using random sampling instead of evenly spaced samples.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of ray tracing is commonly called *distributed ray tracing*, or *distribution ray tracing* because it samples rays from probability distributions.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Distribution ray tracing can also render realistic "soft" shadows from large lights by using a random sample of points on the light when testing for shadowing, and it can simulate chromatic aberration by sampling multiple wavelengths from the spectrum of light.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real surface materials reflect small amounts of light in almost every direction because they have small (or microscopic) bumps and grooves.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A distribution ray tracer can simulate this by sampling possible ray directions, which allows rendering blurry reflections from glossy and metallic surfaces.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, if this procedure is repeated recursively to simulate realistic indirect lighting, and if more than one sample is taken at each surface point, the tree of rays quickly becomes huge.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Another kind of ray tracing, called *path tracing*, handles indirect light more efficiently, avoiding branching, and ensures that the distribution of all possible paths from a light source to the camera is sampled in an unbiased way.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing was often used for rendering reflections in animated films, until path tracing became standard for film rendering.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Films such as Shrek 2 and Monsters University also used distribution ray tracing or path tracing to precompute indirect illumination for a scene or frame prior to rendering it using rasterization.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advances in GPU technology have made real-time ray tracing possible in games, although it is currently almost always used in combination with rasterization.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This enables visual effects that are difficult with only rasterization, including reflection from curved surfaces and interreflective objects, and shadows that are accurate over a wide range of distances and surface orientations.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing support is included in recent versions of the graphics APIs used by games, such as DirectX, Metal, and Vulkan.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing has been used to render simulated black holes, and the appearance of objects moving at close to the speed of light, by taking spacetime curvature and relativistic effects into account during light ray simulation.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity (named after the radiometric quantity of the same name) is a method for rendering objects illuminated by light bouncing off rough or matte surfaces.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of illumination is called *indirect light*, *environment lighting*, *diffuse lighting*, or *diffuse interreflection*, and the problem of rendering it realistically is called *global illumination*.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization and basic forms of ray tracing (other than distribution ray tracing and path tracing) can only roughly approximate indirect light, e.g. by adding a uniform "ambient" lighting amount chosen by the artist.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity techniques are also suited to rendering scenes with *area lights* such as rectangular fluorescent lighting panels, which are difficult for rasterization and traditional ray tracing.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the original radiosity method (first proposed in 1984) now called *classical radiosity*, surfaces and lights in the scene are split into pieces called *patches*, a process called *meshing* (this step makes it a finite element method).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The rendering code must then determine what fraction of the light being emitted or diffusely reflected (scattered) by each patch is received by each other patch.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These fractions are called *form factors* or *view factors* (first used in engineering to model radiative heat transfer).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The form factors are multiplied by the albedo of the receiving surface and put in a matrix.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The lighting in the scene can then be expressed as a matrix equation (or equivalently a system of linear equations) that can be solved by methods from linear algebra.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Solving the radiosity equation gives the total amount of light emitted and reflected by each patch, which is divided by area to get a value called *radiosity* that can be used when rasterizing or ray tracing to determine the color of pixels corresponding to visible parts of the patch.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time rendering, this value (or more commonly the irradiance, which does not depend on local surface albedo) can be pre-computed and stored in a texture (called an *irradiance map*) or stored as vertex data for 3D models.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This feature was used in architectural visualization software to allow real-time walk-throughs of a building interior after computing the lighting.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The large size of the matrices used in classical radiosity (the square of the number of patches) causes problems for realistic scenes.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Practical implementations may use Jacobi or Gauss-Seidel iterations, which is equivalent (at least in the Jacobi case) to simulating the propagation of light one bounce at a time until the amount of light remaining (not yet absorbed by surfaces) is insignificant.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Form factors may be recomputed when they are needed, to avoid storing a complete matrix in memory.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The quality of rendering is often determined by the size of the patches, e.g. very fine meshes are needed to depict the edges of shadows accurately.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important improvement is *hierarchical radiosity*, which uses a coarser mesh (larger patches) for simulating the transfer of light between surfaces that are far away from one another, and adaptively sub-divides the patches as needed.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This allows radiosity to be used for much larger and more complex scenes.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Alternative and extended versions of the radiosity method support non-Lambertian surfaces, such as glossy surfaces and mirrors, and sometimes use volumes or "clusters" of objects as well as surface patches.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Simplified and partially precomputed versions of radiosity are widely used for real-time rendering, combined with techniques such as *octree radiosity* that store approximations of the light field.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As part of the approach known as *physically based rendering*, **path tracing** has become the dominant technique for rendering realistic scenes, including effects for movies.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For example, the popular open source 3D software Blender uses path tracing in its Cycles renderer.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Like *distributed ray tracing*, path tracing is a kind of *stochastic* or *randomized* ray tracing that uses Monte Carlo or Quasi-Monte Carlo integration.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was proposed and named in 1986 by Jim Kajiya in the same paper as the rendering equation.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Kajiya suggested reducing the noise present in the output images by using *stratified sampling* and *importance sampling* for making random decisions such as choosing which ray to follow at each step of a path.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Even with these techniques, path tracing would not have been practical for film rendering, using computers available at the time, because the computational cost of generating enough samples to reduce variance to an acceptable level was too high.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Monster House, the first feature film rendered entirely using path tracing, was not released until 20 years later.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In its basic form, path tracing is inefficient (requiring too many samples) for rendering caustics and scenes where light enters indirectly through narrow spaces.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Attempts were made to address these weaknesses in the 1990s.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Metropolis light transport* samples paths by modifying paths that were previously traced, spending more time exploring paths that are similar to other "bright" paths, which increases the chance of discovering even brighter paths.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Multiple importance sampling* provides a way to reduce variance when combining samples from more than one sampling method, particularly when some samples are much noisier than the others.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This later work was summarized and expanded upon in Eric Veach's 1997 PhD thesis, which helped raise interest in path tracing in the computer graphics community.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The Arnold renderer, first released in 1998, proved that path tracing was practical for rendering frames for films, and that there was a demand for unbiased and physically based rendering in the film industry; other commercial and open source path tracing renderers began appearing.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Computational cost was addressed by rapid advances in CPU and cluster performance.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing's relative simplicity and its nature as a Monte Carlo method (sampling hundreds or thousands of paths per pixel) have made it attractive to implement on a GPU, especially on recent GPUs that support ray tracing acceleration technology such as Nvidia's RTX and OptiX.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport are more difficult to implement efficiently on a GPU.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Techniques have been developed to denoise the output of path tracing, reducing the number of paths required to achieve acceptable quality, at the risk of losing some detail or introducing small-scale artifacts that are more objectionable than noise.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks are now widely used for this purpose.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Research into improving path tracing continues.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Many variations of bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport have been explored, and ways of combining path tracing with photon mapping.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent *path guiding* approaches construct approximations of the light field probability distribution in each volume of space, so paths can be sampled more effectively.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] By combining denoising and hardware ray tracing acceleration, it is now practical to use path tracing for real-time rendering.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to performance constraints, biased techniques such as a radiance cache may be incorporated.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Spatiotemporal reservoir resampling (ReSTIR) aims to improve the quality of real-time path tracing and allow more complex lighting by reusing samples (paths) from previous frames and adjacent pixels.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As of 2003, machine learning (ML) techniques were being used in other areas of computer graphics, such as texture synthesis, fitting surfaces to point clouds, and fitting curves to motion capture data.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The use of ML for rendering expanded with the availability of GPUs that can evaluate neural networks (especially convolutional neural networks) quickly.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks and Gaussian mixture models have been used in conjunction with rendering techniques such as path tracing to encode bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs), or to encode cached radiance at points in space (for biased acceleration of rendering or for path guiding).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural radiance fields (NeRFs) take the latter approach to an extreme, encoding radiance at all points in a volume, and using evaluation of this approximation as the primary rendering method.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the most widely used applications of machine learning in rendering is denoising of path traced images (in practice, most path tracing now likely uses such a denoiser).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Denoisers specialized for real-time rendering can work with very low sample counts and improve temporal coherence to reduce flickering.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering is usually limited by available computing power and memory bandwidth, and so specialized hardware has been developed to speed it up ("accelerate" it), particularly for real-time rendering.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware features such as a framebuffer for raster graphics are required to display the output of rendering smoothly in real time.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware acceleration does not replace the use of software for rendering, rather it speeds up selected operations or calculations using dedicated circuits, or runs portions of the software's code on a different type of processor.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the era of vector monitors (also called *calligraphic displays*), a display processing unit (DPU) was a dedicated CPU or coprocessor that maintained a list of visual elements and redrew them continuously on the screen by controlling an electron beam.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advanced DPUs such as Evans & Sutherland's Line Drawing System-1 (and later models produced into the 1980s) incorporated 3D coordinate transformation features to accelerate rendering of wire-frame images.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Evans & Sutherland also made the Digistar planetarium projection system, which was a vector display that could render both stars and wire-frame graphics (the vector-based Digistar and Digistar II were used in many planetariums, and a few may still be in operation).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A Digistar prototype was used for rendering 3D star fields for the film Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan – some of the first 3D computer graphics sequences ever seen in a feature film.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Shaded 3D graphics rendering in the 1970s and early 1980s was usually implemented on general-purpose computers, such as the PDP-10 used by researchers at the University of Utah.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was difficult to speed up using specialized hardware because it involves a pipeline of complex steps, requiring data addressing, decision-making, and computation capabilities typically only provided by CPUs (although dedicated circuits for speeding up particular operations were proposed ).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Supercomputers or specially designed multi-CPU computers or clusters were sometimes used for ray tracing.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Clark and Marc Hannah designed the Geometry Engine, a VLSI chip for performing some of the steps of the 3D rasterization pipeline, and started the company Silicon Graphics (SGI) to commercialize this technology.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Home computers and game consoles in the 1980s contained graphics coprocessors that were capable of scrolling and filling areas of the display, and drawing sprites and lines, though they were not useful for rendering realistic images.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Towards the end of the 1980s PC graphics cards and arcade games with 3D rendering acceleration began to appear, and in the 1990s such technology became commonplace.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Today, even low-power mobile processors typically incorporate 3D graphics acceleration features.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The 3D graphics accelerators of the 1990s evolved into modern GPUs.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] GPUs are general-purpose processors, like CPUs, but they are designed for tasks that can be broken into many small, similar, mostly independent sub-tasks (such as rendering individual pixels) and performed in parallel.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to their origins, GPUs typically still provide specialized hardware acceleration for some steps of a traditional 3D rasterization pipeline, including hidden surface removal using a z-buffer, and texture mapping with mipmaps, but these features are no longer always used.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs have features to accelerate finding the intersections of rays with a bounding volume hierarchy, to help speed up all variants of ray tracing and path tracing, as well as neural network acceleration features sometimes useful for rendering.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering algorithms will run efficiently on a GPU only if they can be implemented using small groups of threads that perform mostly the same operations.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As an example of code that meets this requirement: when rendering a small square of pixels in a simple ray-traced image, all threads will likely be intersecting rays with the same object and performing the same lighting computations.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For performance and architectural reasons, GPUs run groups of around 16-64 threads called *warps* or *wavefronts* in lock-step (all threads in the group are executing the same instructions at the same time).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If not all threads in the group need to run particular blocks of code (due to conditions) then some threads will be idle, or the results of their computations will be discarded, causing degraded performance.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, the term *hardware rendering* (possibly an abbreviation of "hardware accelerated rendering" or "hardware-assisted rendering") was sometimes used to mean rendering using a hardware-accelerated rasterization pipeline (typically for real-time rendering).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In contrast, *software rendering* meant offline rendering using software that was not limited by the capabilities of graphics hardware, and could use more realistic and higher quality techniques.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Both hardware and software have evolved, and although these terms are still used, their meaning may now be context-dependent.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When OpenGL and Direct3D were introduced in the 1990s, there was a need to use these APIs on computers that did not have hardware acceleration for 3D graphics.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] "Fallback" rendering implementations were provided that did not require special hardware, and these are sometimes called "software renderers" (today hardware acceleration is almost always available, and these CPU-only implementations are used primarily for testing).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] More recently, "software rendering" may also mean rendering that does not use graphics APIs such as OpenGL, Metal, Direct3D, or Vulkan.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Types of renderers that in the past might have been called "software renderers" (e.g. path tracing renderers used for offline rendering for movies) now commonly use GPU acceleration, often via APIs such as CUDA or OpenCL, which are not graphics-specific.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Since these latter APIs allow running C++ code on a GPU, it is now possible to run the same rendering code on either a CPU or GPU.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The following is a rough timeline of frequently mentioned rendering techniques, including areas of current research.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that even in cases where an idea was named in a specific paper, there were almost always multiple researchers or teams working in the same area (including earlier related work).
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When a method is first proposed it is often very inefficient, and it takes additional research and practical efforts to turn it into a useful technique.
[src:cryengine/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The list focuses on academic research and does not include hardware.
